Euthydemia
Euthydemia or Euthymedeia (Greek: Ευθυμεδεία) was the ancient city of Sagala belonging to the Bactrian Dynasty, now located in modern-day Sialkot, Pakistan.{"citetype": "book", "date": "2010-06-24", "title": "The Greeks in Bactria and India", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=-HeJS3nE9cAC&pg=PA89&dq=euthydemus+ptolemy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQt4Sp-YHZAhUExWMKHTQrC2sQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=euthymedia%20ptolemy&f=false", "language": "en", "publisher": "Cambridge University Press", "isbn": "9781108009416", "last": "Tarn", "first": "William Woodthorpe"} The British classical scholar William Woodthorpe Tarn, suggested that "Euthydemia" was never assigned as a new name for ancient Sagala, and that the name was actually Euthymedeia. The altered name was suggested to have been a 1738 alteration made by historian T Beyer.{"citetype": "book", "date": "2013-06-02", "title": "The Hellenistic Settlements in the East from Armenia and Mesopotamia to Bactria and India", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=3aabFPHxRPUC&pg=PA324&lpg=PA324&dq=euthydemia+beyer&source=bl&ots=UooWLIbriq&sig=nJE1rLQ1X3xrMydoq_Y0_g4PZ0s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ36ed94HZAhVJ7GMKHeHADTEQ6AEIQzAK#v=onepage&q=euthydemia%20beyer&f=false", "language": "en", "publisher": "University of California Press", "isbn": "9780520953567", "last": "Cohen", "first": "Getzel M."} The city was mentioned by Ptolemy in his 1st century BCE work, Geography.{"citetype": "book", "date": "1960", "title": "Journal of Indian History", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=nB-2AAAAIAAJ&q=euthydemus+sialkot+ptolemy&dq=euthydemus+sialkot+ptolemy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiunOaK-YHZAhUG72MKHYQRDX8Q6AEIPTAE", "language": "en"}{"citetype": "book", "date": "2010-06-24", "title": "The Greeks in Bactria and India", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=-HeJS3nE9cAC&pg=PA89&dq=euthydemus+ptolemy&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQt4Sp-YHZAhUExWMKHTQrC2sQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=euthymedia%20ptolemy&f=false", "language": "en", "publisher": "Cambridge University Press", "isbn": "9781108009416", "last": "Tarn", "first": "William Woodthorpe"}
In the 2nd century BCE, Euthydemia also known as Sagala,{"citetype": "book", "date": "1827", "title": "Transactions of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland, Volume 1", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=OUs1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA329&dq=Claudius+Ptolemy+lahore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM4dmWibzVAhWJMo8KHWdJA9EQ6AEIJzAB#v=onepage&q=Sangala&f=false", "publisher": "Parbury, Allen, & Co.", "pages": "328, 329"} was made the capital of the Indo-Greek kingdom by the buddhist King Milinda, as recorded in the Buddhist text Milinda Panha.{"citetype": "book", "last1": "McEvilley", "first1": "Thomas", "date": "2012", "title": "The Shape of Ancient Thought: Comparative Studies in Greek and Indian Philosophies", "url": "https://books.google.com/books?id=gbjelOMYyN8C&pg=PT568&dq=sagala+sialkot&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLk9Opq6DUAhUBU2MKHVAICR4Q6AEIUTAI#v=onepage&q=sagala%20sialkot&f=false", "publisher": "Skyhorse Publishing", "isbn": "9781581159332", "accessdate": "2 June 2017"}

